For the last three days, the positivity rate in the country has gone below five per cent, the standard measure by the World Health Organisation (WHO) of how serious the pandemic is.
On Wednesday, the positivity rate stood at 5.6 per cent while on Tuesday, it was 4.7 per cent. On Monday, it stood at 4.5 per cent, the lowest since September 2020.
According Dr Ahmed Kalebi, a pathologist, and the CEO Lancet Group of Laboratories, last week recorded the lowest tally of new Covid-19 cases in 11 weeks since the second wave “as Covid-19 curve continues to steeply decline after the peak 6 weeks ago”.
However, experts have warned that the rate could go up in the coming days due to the Christmas and New Year festivities. The former city governor is seeking to stop the IEBC from conducting Nairobi gubernatorial by-election. The affected routes are Ruiru, Embakasi, Kikuyu and Syokimau. The former city governor is seeking to stop the IEBC from conducting Nairobi gubernatorial by-election. The affected routes are Ruiru, Embakasi, Kikuyu and Syokimau.